# Computa Make No Mistakes

When this rule applies, execute the task with a phased, evidence-first verification loop.

Core rules:

- Treat `/computa-export-control <task>` as the research/intelligence entrypoint for massive projects: research requirements, codebase, technologies, packages, prior art, skills/MCPs/tools, technical specs when needed, implementation strategy when hard engineering issues or missing-key testability need resolution, security/performance/UI audit-suite documentation when a codebase/app exists, then design and execute sequential `/computa-4d-chess` campaigns.
- Treat `/computa-4d-chess <task>` as the Super-Phase one-shot entrypoint for ultra-long autonomous tasks, large edits, major system additions, and build-from-scratch projects. Run architect, build, Super-Phase adversarial review, Super-Phase judge/verifier review, then execute approved Super-Phases through `/computa-make-no-mistakes`.
- Every 4D Chess plan must include final `SP-999-post-run-security-audit`, executed through `/computa-make-no-mistakes` with a nested `/security-audit` task before appending 4D `session_completed`.
- Treat `/computa-make-no-mistakes <task>` as a request to invoke the phase-level suite for debugging/implementation tasks with small-medium scope, code edits, system additions, and medium-scope scratch builds: `computa-swarm-verify`, `computa-swarm-verify-setup`, `computa-swarm-verify-investigate`, `computa-swarm-verify-tdd-qa`, `computa-swarm-verify-swarms`, and `computa-swarm-verify-closeout`.
- Treat `/computa-execution-queue` as the queue manager. Every Export Control, 4D Chess, and Computa invocation must expand child skills, phases, tasks, review gates, docs hooks, and closeout gates into `docs/computa-artifacts/execution-queue.csv` before executing them. The queue is dependency-aware, not FIFO.
- Treat `/computa-resume` as the recovery entrypoint: inspect `docs/computa-artifacts/execution-queue.csv`, `activity-log.csv`, `session-ledger.csv`, `secrets-needed/secrets-needed.csv`, and local ledgers to identify the latest safe resume point before executing more work.
- Treat `/computa-secrets-needed` as the shared ledger for API keys, OAuth credentials, webhook secrets, model-provider keys, deployment secrets, dashboard credentials, target env/platform paths, blocked verification, and safe `@Computer` handoff prompts. Never store actual secret values in code, artifacts, logs, reports, screenshots, terminal output, or git.
- Treat `/computa-md` as explicit-only. Use it only when invoked to archive existing `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md`/harness docs and write concise task-local docs with artifact and resume paths.
- If Export Control or 4D Chess targets an existing codebase, audit the codebase first. Do not finalize architecture, technology choices, prior-art reuse, or campaign/Super-Phase design from chat context alone.
- Save the raw user request immediately to `user-task.md` before rewriting or planning from memory.
- Run `computa-speak` immediately after raw request capture. Save `normalized-task.md` and `prompt-normalization-log.md`; downstream work analyzes `normalized-task.md` and cross-checks `user-task.md`.
- Create `docs/` if missing before creating `docs/computa-artifacts/`.
- Create all plan, phase, task, subtask, issue, blocker, evidence, and final report artifacts under `<invocation-root>/docs/computa-artifacts/`.
- Keep actual architecture docs as a sibling directory at `docs/architecture/`; never place them under `docs/computa-artifacts/`.
- If `docs/computa-artifacts/` is inside a git repo, add it to `.gitignore` if missing.
- Support multiple sessions: standalone Export Control sessions under `docs/computa-artifacts/export-control/EC-.../`, standalone 4D sessions under `docs/computa-artifacts/4d-chess/4D-.../`, standalone Computa sessions under `docs/computa-artifacts/computa/CMN-.../`, and nested child sessions under their parent session directories.
- Maintain `docs/computa-artifacts/activity-log.csv` with session, queue, campaign, Super-Phase, phase, task, secret-needed, and 4D security-audit start/finish/block/defer events as they happen. Do not duplicate subtask rows there.
- Maintain root and session-local `execution-queue.csv/.md`. Invocation expands the queue; execution consumes the highest-priority unblocked item. Do not mark a skill/session complete while required queue rows are queued, ready, running, or review_needed.
- If `docs/architecture/` exists, read it first, then verify against source. If it is missing or stale and the task needs handoff docs, use `computa-docs-architecture`.
- In Export Control, create `technical-spec/` before 4D campaign design when the work needs concrete engineering contracts. Include current/target state, module boundaries, component/API/data/integration design, security/privacy, rollout/backcompat, observability, test strategy, implementation slices, and acceptance contract.
- In Export Control, create `implementation-strategy/` before 4D campaign design when hard engineering issues, provider integrations, missing keys, migrations, state/concurrency risks, unclear testability, or rollout hazards could affect implementation. Resolve strategy, keyless tests, integration risks, and campaign readiness before launching 4D.
- In Export Control, run the standalone audit suite before final 4D campaign design for existing codebases/apps. Run `security-audit`, `performance-audit`, and `ui-audit` in documentation mode, produce category findings plus `standalone-audits/remediation-backlog.csv`, then make 4D campaigns implement the accepted backlog.
- When any Export Control, 4D Chess, or Computa subworkflow is run independently, use the same available dependency capabilities: terse communication, planning, TDD, investigation, parallel agents, adversarial review, completion verification, Playwright/browser QA, Context7/current docs, and web research when current external information matters.
- Phase 0: create the plan directory, `plan.md`, `master-task-ledger.csv`, `issues-and-blockers.md/csv`, phase directories, task directories, subtask ledgers, and `reports/`.
- Phase 1: run an orientation audit before implementation. Create `maps/map-index.md`, `architecture-docs-map.md`, `task-scope-map.md`, `codebase-map.md`, `flow-map.md`, `test-and-command-map.md`, `risk-map.md`, `secrets-map.md`, `modularity-map.md`, `map-change-log.md`, and `map-change-ledger.csv` so later phases can reference the working model.
- Phase 2: investigate before implementation. Read source truth, reference and update the maps, verify current and expected behavior, identify edge cases and coverage gaps, run baseline commands, reproduce the issue or prove the gap, and create failing evidence where possible.
- Maps may change at any time as work reveals new information. Track every material map update in both `maps/map-change-log.md` and `maps/map-change-ledger.csv`.
- Build/spec/test as far as possible when secrets are missing. Missing keys are a keyless-test-design problem, not a reason to stop. Use env var names, placeholders, mocks, fakes, provider adapters, contract tests, fixtures, dry-run modes, runtime guards, and missing-secret tests. Mark only real credential-dependent runtime/deploy verification as blocked.
- Use TDD for behavior changes: failing test first, smallest fix, passing test after.
- Run unit, integration, smoke, runtime, and browser-visible QA as relevant. Use the available browser automation tools for real UI checks.
- Prefer small, modular, readable components over giant files.
- Run swarms only on independent work. Never parallelize overlapping files, shared servers, browser sessions, databases, dashboards, queues, deployments, migrations, or dependent subtasks.
- After every task: run one adversarial reviewer per subtask, then one judge/verifier per subtask. Only implement approved recommendations.
- After every phase: run the architecture-docs update hook, then one adversarial reviewer per task, then one judge/verifier per task. Do not close the phase until each task is approved complete, approved deferred, or blocked with evidence.
- For 4D Chess: review each Super-Phase after creation and review the overall Super-Phase plan before execution. Use one adversarial reviewer per Super-Phase followed by one judge/verifier per Super-Phase.
- For 4D Chess closeout: execute final `SP-999-post-run-security-audit` through `/computa-make-no-mistakes`, create `security-audit/` artifacts, run the full `/security-audit` loop or document an explicit N/A/blocker, then adversarially review and judge/verify the security audit outcome.
- Keep CSV and Markdown ledgers plus `docs/computa-artifacts/secrets-needed/` current. Mark work done only after evidence exists.
- Make one commit per completed task only after verification passes and commits are allowed.
- Do not push unless explicitly asked.

Final reports required under `reports/`:

- `final-summary.md`
- `verification-needed.md`
- `blockers-and-open-issues.md`
- `task-gap-analysis.md`
- `implementation-strategy.md`
- `secrets-needed.md`
- `new-issues-found.md`

Reports may be combined only when clearer, but every category must remain present as an explicit heading.

Do not claim completion unless the final response includes exact verification commands, failing-before evidence or documented exception, passing-after evidence, runtime QA, edge cases, report paths, architecture-docs status, secrets-needed status, remaining risks, gaps, blockers, new issues fixed, and new issues not fixed.

Also include the map artifacts created and the map change log/ledger paths.

Golden rule: evidence before assertions. Never say "it works" without verification command output and runtime proof.
